  </sideBySide>
  <p>
    <alert>Remark</alert>
    Notice that this gives us the exactly same information, just re-arranged a bit, as from the last slide. The underlying mathematical fact that we are not going to prove in this class (but would be covered in Abstract Algebra), is that it <alert>does not matter</alert> which representative for the remainder you use for operations. They all work equally well and yield the same information. Depending on what you're trying to accomplish, one choice might be more <em>useful</em> than another, as we will see later this semester.
  </p>
  <p>
    <alert>Practice:</alert>
    This time let's just do the multiplication tables with two different sets of transversals. First we'll use the same idea as in the example above. For the second set, we'll use an entirely different set of transversals. Make sure to put your answers in terms of the transversal used in the index row/column of the table!
  </p>
  <p>
